# ✈️ Journey — Travel Experience Listing Platform

A full-stack web application where experience providers can create an account and publish travel experiences for travelers to discover.

🔗 **Live Demo:** [https://journey-beta.vercel.app] 
📁 **GitHub:** [https://github.com/Samudhi913/journey]

---

## Project Overview

Journey is a simplified web platform that connects travelers with unique travelling experiences. Users can register, log in, and publish their travel listings. Any visitor can browse the public feed and view listing details without needing an account.

---

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|-----------|
| Frontend | React, React Router, Axios |
| Backend | Node.js, Express |
| Database | MongoDB Atlas, Mongoose |
| Authentication | JSON Web Tokens (JWT), bcryptjs |
| Deployment | Vercel (frontend), Render (backend) |

---

## Setup Instructions

### Prerequisites
- Node.js installed
- MongoDB Atlas account (free tier)

### 1. Clone the repository
```bash
git clone https://github.com/Samudhi913/journey.git
cd journey
```

### 2. Set up the backend
```bash
cd backend
npm install
```

Create a `.env` file in the `backend/` folder:
```
PORT=5000
MONGO_URI=your_mongodb_connection_stringmongodb+srv://Samudhi:Hiranya2005@journey.mzwcj06.mongodb.net/?appName=Journey
JWT_SECRET=mysecretkey123
```

Start the backend:
```bash
npm run dev
```

### 3. Set up the frontend
```bash
cd ../journey-frontend
npm install
npm start
```

The app will open at `http://localhost:3000`

> **Note:** The backend is hosted on Render's free tier and may take 30–60 seconds to wake up on the first request after a period of inactivity.

---

## Features Implemented

### Core Features
- ✅ User registration and login
- ✅ JWT-based authentication with protected routes
- ✅ User logout
- ✅ Create travel experience listings (title, location, image URL, description, price)
- ✅ Public feed showing all listings newest to oldest
- ✅ Listing cards showing image, title, location, description, creator name, and time posted
- ✅ Listing detail page with full information

---

## Architecture & Key Decisions

### Why this tech stack?
React was chosen for the frontend due to its component-based architecture, which makes it easy to build reusable UI elements like listing cards and forms. Node.js with Express was chosen for the backend because it pairs naturally with React and allows for a JavaScript-only codebase across the full stack. MongoDB was selected as the database because its document-based structure maps directly to the listing and user data models without requiring complex relational schemas.

### How authentication works
Authentication is handled using JSON Web Tokens (JWT). When a user registers or logs in, the server validates their credentials, hashes passwords using bcryptjs, and returns a signed JWT token. This token is stored in the browser's localStorage and attached to every subsequent API request via an Axios request interceptor in the `Authorization` header. Protected backend routes use a middleware function that verifies the token before allowing access. If the token is missing or invalid, the request is rejected with a 401 error.

### How travel listings are stored
Listings are stored in a MongoDB Atlas collection using a Mongoose schema with the following fields: `title`, `location`, `imageUrl`, `description`, `price` (optional), and `createdBy` (a reference to the User who created it). The `createdBy` field uses Mongoose's `populate()` method to retrieve the creator's username when fetching listings, avoiding the need to store duplicate user data. Listings are sorted by `createdAt` in descending order so the newest always appear first in the feed.

### One improvement I would implement with more time
I would add image upload support instead of requiring an image URL. Currently users must provide an external image link, which is not intuitive. I would integrate a service like Cloudinary to allow direct image uploads from the create listing form, storing only the returned image URL in the database. This would make the platform significantly easier to use for non-technical users.

I would also add features such as responsive mobile UI which would help the user to view through the mobile easily. I would also add a favourites tab to allow them to keep their most favourite experiences separately and come back to them easily in the future.

---

## Product Thinking Question

**If this platform had 10,000 travel listings, what changes would you make to improve performance and user experience?**

With 10,000 listings, loading everything at once would make the feed extremely slow and create a poor user experience. The first change I would implement is pagination or infinite scroll on the feed, fetching listings in batches of 12–20 at a time rather than all at once. I would also add database indexing on fields like `createdAt`, `location`, and `title` in MongoDB so queries run faster as the dataset grows. A search and filtering feature would become essential at this scale, allowing travelers to filter by location, price range, or keywords rather than scrolling through hundreds of cards. For repeated queries, I would introduce server-side caching using a tool like Redis to store frequently requested results and reduce database load. On the frontend, I would implement lazy loading for images so only visible images are loaded, which would significantly reduce initial page load time. Finally, I would consider moving to a CDN for static assets and optimizing image sizes to further improve performance for users across different regions.